      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>Economic downturns hit HVAC businesses hard. During the 2008 recession, 23% of HVAC contractors went out of business, and the 2020 pandemic caused a 35% drop in new installations. However, companies with recession-proof strategies not only survived but grew market share while competitors struggled.</p>

        <p>Based on analysis of 500+ HVAC companies that thrived during economic downturns, this guide provides specific strategies to maintain revenue when customers tighten their belts. We'll cover the exact revenue mix, pricing strategies, and operational changes that separate survivors from casualties.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="economic-indicators">Understanding Economic Indicators for HVAC</h2>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>HVAC businesses face unique challenges during recessions. New construction drops 45-60% in the first year of economic downturns, directly impacting installation revenue. However, repair and maintenance work typically decreases only 10-20%, creating opportunities for prepared contractors.</p>

        <p>Leading indicators to monitor include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Building permits</strong>: Drop 6 months before installation revenue declines</li>
          <li><strong>Consumer confidence index</strong>: Predicts discretionary HVAC spending</li>
          <li><strong>Local unemployment rates</strong>: Each 1% increase reduces service calls by 3-5%</li>
          <li><strong>Energy prices</strong>: Higher costs drive efficiency upgrade demand</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Companies tracking these metrics adjust strategies 90-120 days ahead of competitors, maintaining revenue stability when others see 25-40% declines.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="maintenance-contracts">Building Recession-Proof Revenue Streams</h2>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>Maintenance contracts provide the most recession-resistant revenue. While installation sales can drop 50% overnight, customers rarely cancel existing service agreements. Companies with strong maintenance bases report 60% more stable revenue during downturns.</p>

        <p>The optimal revenue mix for recession resistance:</p>
      </div>

