      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>To build a recession-resistant maintenance base:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Price maintenance at 8-12% of system value annually</strong>: A $5,000 system should generate $400-600 in annual maintenance revenue</li>
          <li><strong>Include parts and labor</strong>: Comprehensive plans retain customers 3x longer than basic plans</li>
          <li><strong>Offer monthly billing</strong>: Spreads costs and reduces cancellations by 40%</li>
          <li><strong>Bundle priority service</strong>: Guaranteed 24-hour response times command 20% premium pricing</li>
        </ol>

        <p>Companies using <a href="https://go.getjobber.com/bo42cjptz4m2" rel="sponsored nofollow">Jobber's recurring billing features</a> report 35% higher maintenance contract retention because automated billing reduces payment friction and late fees.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="diversification">Service Diversification Strategy</h2>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>Smart diversification creates multiple revenue streams that don't all decline simultaneously. While luxury installations drop 50% in recessions, basic maintenance and emergency repairs remain stable.</p>

        <p>High-opportunity services during downturns:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Indoor air quality solutions</strong>: $200-800 per installation, driven by health concerns</li>
          <li><strong>Duct cleaning and sealing</strong>: $300-600 average ticket, immediate comfort improvements</li>
          <li><strong>Smart thermostat installations</strong>: $200-400 service calls with 40% margins</li>
          <li><strong>Energy efficiency audits</strong>: $150-300 service calls that lead to future work</li>
          <li><strong>Commercial maintenance</strong>: Businesses maintain HVAC to protect assets</li>
        </ul>

        <p>The key is offering services with different economic sensitivities. When residential new construction drops, commercial maintenance remains stable. When discretionary upgrades decline, emergency repairs continue.</p>
      </div>

